In cooperation with the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission, Nautilus Direct (doing business as Bowflex) is voluntarily recalling the Bowflex Power Pro Fitness Machines with the Lat Tower attachment to address two safety issues. First, the backboard bench of the Power Pro can unexpectedly break in the incline position and collapse during use which can injure the user. Second, the Lat Tower itself can rotate forward and fall during use, also posing a risk of injury to a user. We have received many reports of the backboard breaking, causing neck and back injuries. We have also received reports of the Lat Tower rotating, causing injuries. Because your safety is very important to us, stop using your backboard bench and the Lat Tower and contact us for a free repair or replacement. At Bowflex, your safety and satisfaction is our concern. We apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused.

The trombone (German: Posaune, Italian, French: trombone) is a musical instrument in the brass family. As with all brass instruments, sound is produced when the player's vibrating lips cause the air column inside the instrument to vibrate. Nearly all trombones use a telescoping slide mechanism to alter the pitch instead of the valves used by other brass instruments. The valve trombone is an exception, using three valves similar to those on a trumpet, and the superbone has valves and a slide.

aw firm Holden Smith has supported the sale of world-renowned trombone manufacturer Michael Rath Trombones for an undisclosed sum.

The Huddersfield instrument maker has been acquired by global musical instrument retailer John Packer Musical Instruments.

Rob Kelly, director and head of corporate at Holden Smith, said: Michael Rath trombones are found in almost every conceivable musical situation, from symphony orchestras and opera houses to film and television studios. They are made in Huddersfield, but sold across the world, with the USA being a particularly important market.

It has been a pleasure to support owners Michael and Nicola Rath through the acquisition by Taunton-based John Packer Musical Instruments, acting for them with the sale of the entire issued share capital of the company.

Another option is MegaHobby where you can find over 50,000 products for model building with same-day shipping. A subtype of hobby stores are game stores that sell jigsaw puzzles, card games, board games, and role-playing games with community space for enthusiasts to mingle.

A hobby shop (or hobby store) sells recreational items for hobbyists. Classical hobby stores specialize in modeling and craft supplies and specialty magazines for model airplanes (military craft, private airplanes, and airliners), model trains (locomotives, rolling stock, track, power packs, and accessories), ship models, house and building models. Some hobby shops sell R/C cars, pinewood derby kits, boats, and model or remote control planes. Some hobby shops may also sell dolls, figures, and collectible coins and stamps. A subtype of hobby shop is a game store, which sells jigsaw puzzles, card and board games, and role-playing games. Such stores sometimes may also contain community space for hobbyists (gamers) to mingle and play games. In recent years, board and card game hobby shops have often become part-cafes.

The purported oldest hobby shop in Canada is apparently closing its doors for good.

According to the Maritime Hobbies and Crafts website, the Halifax-based store has closed permanently after 78 years of business.

Maritime Hobbies & Crafts has come to an abrupt end, the statement on the website reads. It's the end of a Canadian institution and what was a beautiful story. We've enjoyed the many, many stories we've heard from customers who remember this shop way back when it was in Scotia Square Mall, and some from even before that.

We'll miss chatting with you and sharing the joy of shared hobby interests.

Worms are many different distantly related bilateral animals that typically have a long cylindrical tube-like body, no limbs, and usually no eyes.
Worms vary in size from microscopic to over 1 meter (3.3 ft) in length for marine polychaete worms (bristle worms); 6.7 metres (22 ft) for the African giant earthworm, Microchaetus rappi; and 58 metres (190 ft) for the marine nemertean worm (bootlace worm), Lineus longissimus.[3] Various types of worm occupy a small variety of parasitic niches, living inside the bodies of other animals. Free-living worm species do not live on land but instead live in marine or freshwater environments or underground by burrowing.

The word "worms" has two common meanings. Biologically, it refers to various long, soft-bodied animals, with the three most common types being flatworms, roundworms, and segmented worms. Medically, it denotes intestinal worms that live as parasites in humans, deriving nourishment from their hosts. Many types of worms can cause health issues in humans. Threadworms, the most common worm infection in Australia, can cause an itchy bottom and redness around the anus. People usually catch threadworms by ingesting their eggs. Worms are diagnosed in the lab from fresh stool samples. Intestinal worm infections are treated with medicines that kill the parasite without harming the person.

Worms are bilateral animals and extremely varied in size, from tiny worms that need a microscope to see up to incredibly long worms half the length of an Olympic swimming pool. They typically have a long cylindrical tube-like body, no limbs, and usually no eyes. Some worms can even infect human and get to your intestines (bowls). Other than the animal, there is also WoRMS which is the world register for marine species. There are even computer worms which are a standalone malware computer program that replicates itself in order to spread to other computers.

The word "worms" has various meanings: biologically, it refers to segmented worms (annelids), roundworms, and flatworms, as well as small, soft-bodied invertebrates; medically, it denotes parasitic worms like hookworms and pinworms; in computing, it describes self-replicating malicious software; idiomatically, it is used in phrases like "opening a can of worms" (creating a complicated situation) and "worm one's way" (acting sneakily); culturally, it can refer to the "Worms" video game series or the "worm" dance move; and geologically, it pertains to worm burrows or fossils found in sedimentary rocks. In german, "earworm" refers to the experience of having a song stuck in your brain. The Kiwi bird has tiny wings hidden underneath their hair-like feathers, and their eggs are the largest in proportion to their body size. This flightless bird, known as the Kiwi, is a national symbol of New Zealand. Informally, 'Kiwi' refers to people from New Zealand, symbolizing national pride.

Kiwifruit (often shortened to kiwi outside New Zealand and Australia) or Chinese gooseberry, is the edible berry of several species of woody vines in the genus Actinidia. The most common cultivar group of kiwifruit (Actinidia deliciosa 'Hayward') is oval, about the size of a large hen's egg: 58 centimetres (23 inches) in length and 4.55.5 cm (12 in) in diameter. Kiwifruit has a thin, fuzzy, fibrous, tart but edible light brown skin and light green or golden flesh with rows of tiny, black, edible seeds. The fruit has a soft texture with a sweet and unique flavour.

The term "kiwi" has multiple meanings based on the context: it commonly refers to the kiwifruit, an edible berry from the genus Actinidia, known for its fuzzy brown skin and vibrant green or golden flesh rich in vitamin C, K, and fiber. Additionally, "kiwi" denotes a flightless bird native to New Zealand from the genus Apteryx, notable for its small size, long beak, hair-like feathers, nocturnal habits, and strong sense of smell. The kiwi bird is also a national symbol of New Zealand. Informally, "Kiwi" is used to refer to people from New Zealand as a term of endearment and national pride. Moreover,"kiwi" can function as a nickname or brand name in various contexts including products and businesses.

Iron (Fe, atomic number 26) is a chemical element that is a common greyish colored metal that rusts in damp air. It is, by mass, the most common element on Earth, forming much of Earth's outer and inner core. It is strong, used in making steel, used in civil engineering, manufacturing and machinery. Ordinary carbon steel is an alloy of iron with carbon, with small amounts of other elements. Alloy steels are stronger carbon steels and have a huge variety of applications including bridges, electricity pylons, cutting tools and rifle barrels. Iron also exists in very small amounts in blood. Iron is important in making hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells, which carry oxygen around the body. A lack of iron can lead to iron deficiency Anemia. Good sources of iron include liver, kidney, red meat, beans. Furthermore, magnets can be made of iron and its alloys and compounds.

What is iron? Iron is a mineral that our bodies need for growth and development. Your body uses iron to make hemoglobin, a protein in red blood cells. Iron is also important for healthy muscles, bone marrow, and organ function. Your body also needs iron to make some hormones. Iron is found naturally in many foods and is added to some fortified food products. Iron is available in supplements, either on its own or as part of many multivitamin/mineral supplements. If you have too little iron, you may develop iron-deficiency anemia. It can cause fatigue, shortness of breath, and trouble with memory and concentration. Treatment for low iron and iron-deficiency anemia is usually with iron supplements.

A tornado is a violently rotating column of air in contact with both the Earth's surface and a cumulonimbus cloud or, in rare cases, the base of a cumulus cloud. Often called a twister or whirlwind, tornadoes occur worldwide, including in Australia, Europe, Africa, Asia, South America, and most often in the United States, where about 1,200 tornadoes hit yearly. Every U.S. state has experienced twisters, with Texas holding the record at an annual average of 120.
Tornadoes can happen at any time of year and any time of day or night, though most occur between 4-9 p.m. To determine a tornado's strength, experts examine the damage it caused. The most violent tornadoes come from supercells, large thunderstorms that have winds already in rotation. About one in a thousand storms becomes a supercell, and one in five or six supercells spawns off a tornado.

It is often referred to as a twister, whirlwind or cyclone. Tornadoes occur frequently in North America. Fortunately, tornadoes can be detected before or as they occur through the use of pulse-Doppler radar. Most tornadoes take on the appearance of a narrow funnel with a small cloud of debris near the ground. Tornadoes may be obscured completely by rain or dust or can have a wide range of colors, depending on the environment in which they form. The most famous tornado was the Tri-State Tornado which happened in the US in 1925. It holds records for path length, duration, and fastest forward speed.It is the deadliest tornado in US history.

Human memory is a biological process involving the brain's neurons and synapses to encode, store, and retrieve information. It is influenced by emotions, context, and meaning, and it can be fallible and subject to distortion over time. In contrast, computer memory is an electronic system designed to store and retrieve digital data. It operates through binary code and is divided into primary memory (RAM) for temporary data storage and secondary memory (hard drives, SSDs) for long-term data storage. Computer memory is precise, consistent, and not influenced by emotions or context. It retains data exactly as inputted and can be easily expanded or modified.

Memory is the power to remember information and past experiences. All memories are stored in our brain. We can divide memories into two categories: short-term memories- of events that occurred recently, and long-term memories- of events that happened a long time ago. A memory can be good, or bad. Memories can reside in our subconscious, so we may not seem to remember them, or they can be in our conscious mind.  Good memories bring us great happiness, but bad memories can be destructive, even leading to post-trauma (PTSD). The last one can be treated, but as our memories can be sometimes be really hard to forget or ignore, and therefore needed the help of professionals.  A well-known memory-related disease is Alzheimer's, which is characterized by the loss of both long-term and short-term memory, and is most common in elderly people.

Twenty years ago, at a particularly stressful time in my mid-40s, I thought I was losing my mind  or at least my memory. I sometimes had trouble coming up with words  initially names, then simple phrases (like referring to the proverbial night owl as a night bird). Each flub made me anxious, which then worsened my memory issues. Listening to my inner hypochondriac, I became convinced I had a brain tumor. I went to see my primary care doctor.

She asked me a series of questions. What year is it? Whats todays date? Whos the president? I was batting 1.000 until she asked me to spell w-o-r-l-d backward, when I faltered. My pulse began to race. Can you count backwards from 100 by sevens? she queried me. I got to 93 but could go no further, which is when I broke down sobbing, convinced Id been right about my diagnosis.

Twenty years ago, at a particularly stressful time in my mid-40s, I thought I was losing my mind  or at least my memory. I sometimes had trouble coming up with words  initially names, then simple phrases (like referring to the proverbial night owl as a night bird). Each flub made me anxious, which then worsened my memory issues. Listening to my inner hypochondriac, I became convinced I had a brain tumor. I went to see my primary care doctor.

She asked me a series of questions. What year is it? Whats todays date? Whos the president? I was batting 1.000 until she asked me to spell w-o-r-l-d backward, when I faltered. My pulse began to race. Can you count backwards from 100 by sevens? she queried me. I got to 93 but could go no further, which is when I broke down sobbing, convinced Id been right about my diagnosis.

Rice: The World's Essential Staple Food
Rice (Oryza sativa) is an edible starchy cereal grain produced by a grass plant in the family Poaceae. As a staple food, rice is essential for roughly half of the world's population, with nearly all of East and Southeast Asia relying heavily on it. Remarkably, 95 percent of the world's rice crop is consumed by humans, making it one of the most important food sources globally. Rice comes in various types such as white rice, brown rice, jasmine rice, and basmati rice. It is incredibly versatile and can be boiled, steamed, or fried. Rice is a fundamental component in many cuisines, including Asian, Middle Eastern, and global dishes. It is also processed into products like rice flour, rice noodles, and rice cereals, and is used in beverages such as Japanese sake.

Rice is a serial grain, that is the seed of the Oryza sativa (Asian rice) grass plant, and less commonly Oryza glaberrima (African rice). Rice is the main food source of more than half of the world's population, particularly Asia and Africa. The rice was first domesticated in Chine almost 10,000 years ago, and was cultivated since then. Most of the world's rice is produced in China and India, but the also consume almost all the rice they grow. In many places in Asia, rice is traditionally grown in rice terraces or fields. Rice is eaten in plain like in the Indian chicken tikka masala, or in other dishes, like the Japanese sushi, curried rice and the Pakistani Dum Biryani. In Japan, Sake, a strong alcoholic beverage, is made from rice.

Rice, (Oryza sativa), edible starchy cereal grain and the grass plant (family Poaceae) by which it is produced.

How to cook rice?
Start by rinsing the rice. Add the rice to a fine-mesh sieve, hold under a tap, and run cold water while stirring. Continue to rinse until the water falling through is clear instead of cloudy.
Meanwhile, in a pot, combine 1.5 c. water and 0.5 tsp. salt. Bring to a boil over high heat, pour the rinsed rice into the pot. Bring the water back to a simmer, then lower the heat, cover the pot, and let it cook for 15 minutes, or until the rice is tender but not mushy.
Then, remove the rice pot from the heat, and cover the pot with a paper towel. Replace the lid over the paper towel or clean kitchen towel to seal it. Let the rice steam for 10 minutes. At last, remove the lid. Fluff the rice with a fork and serve.

China, India, and Indonesia are the largest consumers of rice.

Rice, (Oryza sativa), is an edible starchy cereal grain and a grass plant (family Poaceae) by which it is produced. Roughly one-half of the world population, including virtually all of East and Southeast Asia, is wholly dependent upon rice as a staple food; 95 percent of the worlds rice crop is eaten by humans. Rice can be cooked by boiling or ground into flour. It is consumed alone and in various soups, side dishes, and main dishes in Asian, Middle Eastern, and many other cuisines. Other products that use rice include breakfast cereals, noodles, and alcoholic beverages like Japanese sake. Rice varieties such as Arborio for risottos and Sushi Rice for sushi are popular globally.

Rice, the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa and Oryza glaberrima, is the staple food for more than half of the world's population, particularly in Asia and Africa. Asian rice was domesticated in China some 10,000 years ago, while African rice was domesticated in Africa about 3,000 years ago. Rice is used in a variety of forms such as rice flour, rice noodles, and rice cereals, and is also a key ingredient in beverages like Japanese sake. Remarkably, 95 percent of the world's rice crop is consumed by humans, highlighting its global importance.

The encyclopaedia Britannica traces what was the designer dog fad to the late 20th century when breeders began to cross purebred Poodles with other purebred breeds to obtain a dog with the Poodle's hypoallergenic coat, along with various desirable characteristics from other breeds.
The resulting puppies are called by a portmanteau word made up of syllables (or sounds) from the breed names of the two purebred parents, such as Schnoodle (Schnauzer and Poodle cross), or Shepsky (German Shepherd Dog/Siberian Husky cross). Other purebred breeds are being crossed to provide designer dogs described with an endless range of created labels, such as the Puggle (Pug and Beagle cross).
